Is there a heat island generated by Eugene, Oregon?

A Bootstrapped Estimate of Differences in Temperatures Between Eugene and its surroundings

Damian Satterthwaite - Phillips

Introduction

There are analytical methods for handling the temporal and spatial autocorrelation in data sets like this one, but specifying a model that fits the data well without making potentially spurious assumptions about the structure of the data can be challenging.

Another more “brute force” approach is to create bootstrapped estimates from the existing data. This approach relies on randomly resampling the data many times to effectively simulate what temperatures may be expected under different conditions.

In this case, the variables, elevation, and precipitation are converted to categorical variables: elevation - low/medium/high, and precipitation - none/low/medium/high, and we already a categorical variable 'adjWater', indicating if a location is adjacent to a river or lake. Each locus is further labeled as 'city', for points near the center of the cities (Eugene or Springfield) 'periph', if they are around the edge of the city, and 'rural', if farther away. For each date and set of conditions, we randomly sample temperatures from all loci that meet those conditions, and generate an expected value. We then look at the differences in city and rural values when all other conditions are held constant, and perform statistical analyses on these differences.

Set up

A heat map visualization of the data can be seen here. 

# Clear R memory, and load necessary libraries
rm(list = ls())
library(lattice)

# Warnings are turned off here so that they will not appear in the final
# knitted html file.  Omit this line when running locally.
options(warn = -1)

# Load in the data (change the path as needed)
eug = read.csv('~/Desktop/PRA/uhi/dataComplied/eug2014.csv')

eug$ID = as.factor(eug$ID)
eug$date = as.Date(eug$date)
alpha = 0.01

# Store the number of rows in the data
r = dim(eug)[1]

The next bit of code assigns each locus to city, periph, or rural (this was done simply by eyeballing their locations on Google maps here). Recall that numbering begins at the lower left, with the westernmost column of loci being 1 - 10, the next column to the right 11 - 20, and so forth.

# Subdivide the data into categories:
city = c(115:117, 125:127, 135:137, 145:147, 155:157, 166)
periph = c( 104:108, 114, 118, 124, 128, 134, 138, 144, 148, 154, 158, 164,
            165, 167, 168, 175:177, 186 )
rural = 1:270[-c(city, periph)]

# Create the vector as a column in the eug data frame
distCat = rep('rural', r)
distCat[which(eug$ID %in% city)] = 'city'
distCat[which(eug$ID %in% periph)] = 'periph'
eug$distCat = factor(distCat, levels = c('city', 'periph', 'rural'))
rm(distCat, city, periph, rural)

# Plot to make sure it looks ok
plot(eug$x, eug$y, col = eug$distCat, xlab = 'Longitude', ylab = 'Latitude')

When dividing the numerical variables into categories, we want to do it in such a way that divides the values as evenly as possible, so we maximize the amount of data points in each subset. For precipitation:

Possible subsets of the data

We now have the following categorical variables with the following values:

  • Adjacent to Water - adjWater (TRUE, FALSE)
  • Precipitation -ppt4 (none: 0 mm, low ≤ 2.00 mm > med ≤ 8.52 mm < high)
  • Elevation - elev3 (low ≤ 126 m < med ≤ 143.2m < high)
  • And a distance from city category - distCat (city, periph, or rural)

All in all this makes for 2 * 4 * 3 * 3 = 72 unique subsets of the data, such as: {adjW = T, ppt4 = 'none', elev3 = 'low', and distCat = 'city'} or {adjW = F, ppt4 = 'low', elev3 = 'med', and distCat = 'rural'}, and so on. As a shorthand, each unique subset will be given a four letter code depending on the value of each parameter. E.g., tnlc for first example (True-none-low-city), and flmr for the second (False-low-medium-rural). These will be ordered as: adjWater-ppt4-elev3-distCat, with possible values as: {tf}{nlmh}{lmh}{cpr}

Generate all possible combinations as shorthand abbreviations:

subnames = c()
for (water in c('t', 'f')) {
    for (precip in c('n', 'l', 'm', 'h')) {
        for (elev in c('l', 'm', 'h')) {
            for (dist in c('c', 'p', 'r')) {
                subnames = c( subnames, 
                              paste(water, precip, elev, dist, sep = '') )
            }
        }
    }
}

Next generate each unique subset as a data.frame, and save it to a list.

subset.list = list()

i = 1
for(water in c(T, F)) {
    for (precip in c('none', 'low', 'med', 'high')) {
        for (el in c('low', 'med', 'high')) {
            for (dist in c('city', 'periph', 'rural')) {

                subset.list[[subnames[i]]] = 
                                    subset( eug, adjWater == water & 
                                            ppt4 == precip & 
                                            elev3 == el & 
                                            distCat == dist )
                i = i + 1
            }
        }
    }
}

# A helper function to generate a random color:
rcolor = function(alpha = 1) {
    r = runif(1)
    g = runif(1)
    b = runif(1, 0:(2 - r - g)) # keep it from being too close to white
    rgb(r, g, b, alpha)
}

Analysis - An example

Now what we want to do is the following. For each subset randomly sample the temperature at each day, and plot the raw data, median, and 95% CI. For example, using the largest subset:

# Now, taking 1000 random samplings at each date (with replacement!):
samps = 1000
dates = sort(unique(eug$date))
outM = matrix(nrow = length(dates), ncol = samps + 1)
outM[, 1] = as.Date(dates)

for(d in 1:length(dates)) {
    if (dates[d] %in% subset.list$fnhr$date) {
        outM[d, 2:(samps + 1)] = 
            sample( subset.list$fnhr$temp[ subset.list$fnhr$date == dates[d] ],
                    samps, replace = T )
    }
}

plot( eug$temp ~ eug$date, type = 'n', 
      main = 'Not next to water, No rain, High Elevation, Rural (fnhr)',
      xlab = '2014', ylab = 'Temp (°C)')
color1 = rcolor(alpha = 10 / samps)
for (s in 2:(samps + 1)) {
    lines(outM[, s] ~ outM[, 1], col = color1 )
}

# We can then calculate the expected (median) value and middle 95% from the 
# sampled data:
ci1 = apply(outM[, -1], 1, quantile, probs = c(0.025, 0.5, 0.975), na.rm = T)
lines(ci1[1, ] ~ outM[, 1])
lines(ci1[3, ] ~ outM[, 1])

Now contrast this with the subset with the same values except in the city (fnhc):

outM = matrix(nrow = length(dates), ncol = samps + 1)
outM[, 1] = dates

for(d in 1:length(dates)) {
    if (dates[d] %in% subset.list$fnhc$date) {
        # it turns out that the sample function acts unusally if sampling a 
        # vector, x, of length 1: it treats sample(x) as sample(1:xL), so, a 
        # little extra code here to simply repeat the value if there is only 
        # one.
        # see ?sample
        if (length(subset.list$fnhc$temp[ subset.list$fnhc$date == dates[d] ]) > 1) {
            outM[d, 2:(samps + 1)] = 
                sample( subset.list$fnhc$temp[ subset.list$fnhc$date == dates[d] ],      
                        samps, replace = T )
        } else { 
            outM[d, 2:(samps + 1)] =        
                rep(subset.list$fnhc$temp[ subset.list$fnhc$date == dates[d] ], samps ) 
        }
    }
}

Interpreting the Results

What we see here is that, for many of the dates, the 95% CIs for the city are above those for the surrounding areas, suggesting warmer city temperatures. In other cases the CIs are overlapping suggesting no significant difference on those dates.

However, there are also some caveats. These figures are based on the extant data, which are few for any given date, so the inference is only as good as the diversity of the data. To increase our statistical power, we could calculate the the difference of the median estimate for each day, and then determine if this is significantly different from the null hypothesis: that the temperatures are the same, and hence the difference = 0. (Note that ci1 and ci2 contain the median values as well as the 95 percent CI limits.)

tempDiffs = ci1[2, ] - ci2[2, ] # NOTE: this is rural - city
plot( tempDiffs ~ as.Date(outM[, 1], origin = o), type = 'l', xlab = '2014', 
      main = paste(mainTitle, '\nRural - City') )
abline(h = 0, col = 2)

Something to notice here, is that for the winter months the values are mostly postive (rural is hotter), and for summer, mostly negative (city is hotter). 

boxplot(tempDiffs, notch = T)
abline(h = 0, col = 2)

The notch in the box shows the approximate 95% CI for the median, and it is fully below the null hypothesis line (red), indicating that over the course of the whole year, the difference is negative, i.e., the city is warmer, than the surrounding rural area (for high elevation, on dry days, and loci not adjacent to rivers or lakes).

To analyze this statistically, the Wilcoxon Rank Sum is the appropriate statistic…

wilcox.test(tempDiffs)  

## 
##  Wilcoxon signed rank test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  tempDiffs
## V = 6068.5, p-value = 7.586e-05
## alternative hypothesis: true location is not equal to 0

…and we see that the median value is significantly lower than 0 (p << 0.001)

For those of you who are more comfortable or familiar with the t.test, you may be tempted by:

t.test(tempDiffs)

## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  tempDiffs
## t = -1.177, df = 189, p-value = 0.2407
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.09700411  0.02450417
## sample estimates:
##   mean of x 
## -0.03624997

…but this is problematic as the data are not normally distributed:

hist(tempDiffs)


shapiro.test(tempDiffs)

## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  tempDiffs
## W = 0.8447, p-value = 5.806e-13

…which violates the assumptions of the t-test, as extreme values effect the mean considerably more than they do the median. To exemplify, the means and medians are plotted with and without the 2 most extreme values.

hist(tempDiffs)
abline(v = mean(tempDiffs, na.rm = T), col = 2)
abline(v = median(tempDiffs, na.rm = T), col = 4)

        col = 2, lty = 2 )

So for high elevations, on dry days, and at loci not adjacent to water, the city is expected to be somewhat hotter than the surrounding area by about 0.14°C (0.26°F) year round, or 0.16°C (0.29°F) warmer in the summer and not significantly different in the winter… significant in summer, yes, but the difference is small… What about for the other combinations of values of our parameters (precip, elev, adjWater)?

To examine these, let's first automate the previous analysis to speed things up.

Steamlining Analysis for All Subsets

# Set knitr to F to display all graphics when graph = T. Using quartz() does
# not work in knitr
bootAnalysis = function( s1, s2, samps = 1000, graph = F, alpha = 2 / samps, 
                         knitr = T ) {

    makeMatrix = function(s) { 
        outM = matrix(nrow = length(dates), ncol = samps + 1)
        outM[, 1] = dates

        for(d in 1:length(dates)) {
            if (dates[d] %in% s$date) {
                if (length(s$temp[s$date == dates[d]]) > 1) {
                    outM[d, 2:(samps + 1)] = 
                        sample( s$temp[s$date == dates[d]],      
                                samps, replace = T )
                } else { 
                    outM[d, 2:(samps + 1)] =        
                        rep(s$temp[s$date == dates[d]], samps) 
                }
            }
        }

        outM
    }

    outM = makeMatrix(s1)

    e = s1$elev3[1]; p = s1$ppt4[1]; aw = s1$adjWater[1];

    mainTitle = paste( 'Elevation: ', e, '; Rain: ', p, 
                       '; Adjacent to Water: ', aw, sep = '' )
    if (graph) {
        plot( eug$temp ~ eug$date, type = 'n', 
              main = mainTitle,
              xlab = '2014', ylab = 'Temp (°C)')
        color1 = rcolor(alpha = alpha)

        for (s in 2:(samps + 1)) {
            lines(outM[, s] ~ as.Date(outM[,1], origin = o), col = color1 )
        }
    }

    ci1 = apply( outM[, -1], 1, quantile, probs = c(0.025, 0.5, 0.975), 
                 na.rm = T )

    if (graph) {
        lines(ci1[1, ] ~ as.Date(outM[, 1], origin = o))
        lines(ci1[3, ] ~ as.Date(outM[, 1], origin = o))
    }


    outM = makeMatrix(s2)

    if (graph) {
        color2 = rcolor(alpha = alpha)
        for (s in 2:(samps + 1)) {
            lines(outM[, s] ~ as.Date(outM[,1], origin = o), col = color2 )
        }
    }

    ci2 = apply( outM[, -1], 1, quantile, probs = c(0.025, 0.5, 0.975), 
                 na.rm = T )

    if (graph) {
        lines(ci2[1, ] ~ as.Date(outM[, 1], origin = o), col = 2)
        lines(ci2[3, ] ~ as.Date(outM[, 1], origin = o), col = 2)
    }

    tempDiffs = ci1[2, ] - ci2[2, ] # NOTE: this is rural - city
    hotDiffs = tempDiffs[seas == 'hot']
    coldDiffs = tempDiffs[seas == 'cold']

    wilcoxP = round(wilcox.test(tempDiffs)$p.value, 3)
    wilcoxPHot = round(wilcox.test(hotDiffs)$p.value, 3)
    wilcoxPCold = round(wilcox.test(coldDiffs)$p.value, 3)



    if (graph) {
        if (!knitr) { quartz() }
        plot( tempDiffs ~ as.Date(outM[, 1], origin = o), type = 'l', 
              xlab = '2014', main = paste(mainTitle, '\nRural - City'))
        abline(h = 0, col = 2)

        if (!knitr) { quartz() }
        boxplot( tempDiffs, notch = T, main = mainTitle, 
                 ylab = 'Difference in temperature (Rural - City)')
        abline(h = 0, col = 2)
        legend('topleft', legend = paste('Wilcox Test: p =', wilcoxP))

        if (!knitr) { quartz() }
        par(mfrow = c(3, 1))
        acf( ci1[2, ][!is.na(ci1[2,])], 
             main = paste(mainTitle, 'Rural Temperatures'))
        acf( ci2[2, ][!is.na(ci2[2,])],
             main = paste(mainTitle, 'City Temperatures'))
        acf(tempDiffs[!is.na(tempDiffs)], main = 'Difference (Rural - City)')
        par(mfrow = c(1, 1))

        if (!knitr) { quartz() }
        boxplot( hotDiffs, xlim = c(0.5, 2.5), notch = T, 
                 ylim = range(tempDiffs, na.rm = T),
                 ylab = 'Difference in temperature (Rural - City)' )
        boxplot(coldDiffs, at = 2, add = T, notch = T)
        axis(1, at = c(1, 2), labels = c('hot', 'cold'))
        abline(h = 0, col = 2)
        legend( 'topleft', legend = paste('Wilcox Test: p =', wilcoxPHot),
                bg = rgb(1, 1, 1, alpha = 0.5) )
        legend( 'topright', legend = paste('Wilcox Test: p =', wilcoxPCold),
                bg = rgb(1, 1, 1, alpha = 0.5) )
    }



    data.frame( medDiff = round(median(tempDiffs, na.rm = T), 3),
                p.diff = wilcoxP, 
                medDiffHot = round(median(hotDiffs, na.rm = T), 3),
                p.hot = wilcoxPHot, 
                medDiffCold = round(median(coldDiffs, na.rm = T), 3),
                p.cold = wilcoxPCold )
}

Remember the output is for s1 - s2, so if we follow the convention above and always put the rural date first, and city second, a negative median value for the differences indicates that the city is hotter; a positive value indicates the rural area is hotter. Because of the random sampling, output will differ somewhat on different runs. Use set.seed() to exactly repeat an analysis.

# ?set.seed
set.seed(314159)
# Do the first analysis.  Up the samples to 5000, and for this one, output graphics.  Store results for comparison.

output = bootAnalysis( subset.list$tnlr, subset.list$tnlc, samps = 5000, 
                       graph = T, alpha = 0.006 )


# Note: the above graphs show the temporal autocorrelation functions (ACF) 
# for temperatures at both loci, as well as for the difference.  In all cases 
# the temperatures are highly corrlated (e.g., today's temperature is highly
# correlated with tomorrow's, and even next month's). This autocorrelation 
# violate the iid (independent and identically distributed) assumption 
# necessary for linear models that rely on the ordinary least squares method 
# for fitting... so without correcting for this, it would be a mistake to 
# model temperatures directly.  However, in most cases, the differences in 
# temperatures between city and rural, do not demonstrate this 
# autocorrelation.                 
output = cbind(s1 = 'tnlr', s2 = 'tnlc', output)                       


# Now repeat for all other subsets, but turn off graphics to speed it up. Note: if we use all the data, the loop fails at s = 28, 34, 40, and 46 and 48 due to insufficient data for these subsets to perform the Wilcoxon test.  Hence these values for s have been omitted:
insufficientData = c(28, 34, 40, 46)
sets = seq(2, 48, 2)
sets = sets[-which(sets %in% insufficientData)]
for(s in sets) {
    out = bootAnalysis( subset.list[[testSet[s]]], 
                        subset.list[[testSet[s - 1]]], samps = 5000 )
    out = cbind(s1 = testSet[s], s2 = testSet[s - 1], out)
    output = rbind(output, out)
}

# You will likely get warnings about imperfect p-values in case of ties.  
# This is generally only problematic when p-values are very close to 
# predetermined significance levels.

Discussion

In spite of the few cases we cannot test, for those we can, the results are highly consistent. We see that for nearly all instances for which the differences are significant, it is overwhelmingly the case that city temperatures are warmer than the surrounding areas. The good news is that the difference in temperatures is relatively small. The greatest difference in temperatures was found for high elevations, not adjacent to water, when a lot of precipitation occurs (fhhr/c). In these places and times, city temperatures are, on average 0.73°C (1.3°F) hotter than the surrounding areas. At high elevations, and times of high precipitation, being adjacent to water (thhr/c) diminishes the difference somewhat in the winter (expected that the city will be 0.57°C [1.0°F] warmer), but is somewhat worse in the summer (city is 0.79°C [1.4°F] warmer).

The two instances in which the city was significantly cooler were: (fnlr/c) not adjacent to water, no precipitation, and low elevation (0.05°C cooler [0.1°F] overall; 0.06°C cooler in hot months, not significantly different in cool months) and (fllr/c) not adjacent to water, low precipitation, and low elevation, for which the city is expected to be 0.15°C cooler in summer and 0.03°C cooler in winter.

Some of these results are a bit crude owing to the bootstrapped method, which required conversion of numeric data into categorical data, meaning a loss of information and statistical power. For example, there is a lot of variation within the “high elevation” group, and perhaps very high elevations differ from moderately high ones. Similarly the cooling effect of precipitation may also be sensitive to amounts not captured in the small number of categores. Nevertheless, the results of the output are remarkably consistent, and generally suggest a slight, but significant difference in temperatures, with the city being warmer than its surroundings.
